Natural Language Processing: Text Prediction

Data Science Capstone – Milestone Report

Karthik Arumugham

22 June 2016

Abstract

Natural Language Processing (NLP) is an area of analysis that has great and valuable applications in common daily tasks. It has been used as part of enhanced texting tools such as Swiftkey, anticipate search terms in Google, spell check errors and helping people with speech disabilities. NLP requires a collection of written texts with a common author, source, subject of type (Corpus), and the framework to manipulate it. To facilitate typing on mobile devices, SwiftKey, our corporate partner in this capstone project, builds a smart keyboard that makes it easier for people to type on their mobile devices. One cornerstone of their smart keyboard is predictive text models.

Synopsis

The main goal of this project is to build the next word predictive model given an input word/sentence fragment within the realm of natural language processing. To do, this we are given 3 corpus in three 4 different languages – English, German, Finnish and Russian. But, I chose to only use the English language. There are three different documents that make up the corpus - texts from Twitter feed, news feed, and a blog.

Dataset

The data is originally from: HC Corpora. The datasets for this project can be downloaded from Coursera-SwiftKey Datasets.

As the file sizes are too large, a small 10% random sample of the files have been considered and loaded.

Data Cleaning

There are ~1200 unique characters in the sample dataset. It is also evident that there are foreign language characters such as Chinese, Russian, etc. A quick conversion to ASCII character type reduces the unique characters to ~70. After removing the special characters we are left with ~40 unique characters. . and ' aren’t removed to preserve the sentence structure.

## [1] "Set of unique characters after ASCII conversion"
##  [1] ""   "`"  "^"  "~"  "<"  "="  ">"  "|"  " "  "_"  "-"  ","  ";"  ":" 
## [15] "!"  "?"  "/"  "."  "'"  "("  ")"  "["  "]"  "{"  "}"  "@"  "$"  "*" 
## [29] "\\" "&"  "#"  "%"  "+"  "0"  "1"  "2"  "3"  "4"  "5"  "6"  "7"  "8" 
## [43] "9"  "a"  "b"  "c"  "d"  "e"  "f"  "g"  "h"  "i"  "j"  "k"  "l"  "m" 
## [57] "n"  "o"  "p"  "q"  "r"  "s"  "t"  "u"  "v"  "w"  "x"  "y"  "z"

The following steps were taken to handle the remaining special characters.

  • Website Address: All URLs starting with “http” and “www” are removed.
  • Email Address/Twitter Handle: The @ character is most probably used in an email addresses or a twitter handle. So they are removed first before removing any stray occurences of the symbol.
  • Twitter Hashtags:
  • Twitter Retweet symbol: Any instance of the word RT is removed.
  • End Marks: The sentence splitting works based on endmark characters such as :;?|<>()[]{}!. So these cannot be removed. But to be on a safer side for the algo to work correctly these are replaced with a period ..
  • Apostrophe: This ' is not removed or replaced to preserve the sentence structure of contractions. If this is replaced, then the same needs to be done during the prediction of input text.
  • Other special characters: ,$/&+=@#^%_~-" asterisk and backtick are removed.
  • Numbers: They are replaced with a placeholder n to preserve the sentence structure.
  • Lower case: Lower case conversion is done to help in the further steps.
  • Duplicate words: Consecutive repeated words are usually erroneous and are removed.
  • Extra Spaces: Extra spaces are removed.
  • Time (12-hour clock): Any instances of the form “n a m” or “n p m” are replaced with “n am” or “n pm”
  • Profane words: Data from Twitter has a plethora of abusive words. So a custom compiled profane word dictionary of 1293 words is used to eliminate them from the cleaned dataset.
  • Mis-spellings/Slangs: Datafeed from News and Blog sites would be void of any spelling issues. But Twitter is replete with slangs/mis-spellings. The replacements cannot be automated, as there could be multiple replcements for a particular mistake. Though this step can be processed through packages such as qdap::check_spelling and hunspell, it requires manual intervention to pick the correct word. So this is beyond the scope for now.
  • Sentence length: Remove sentences with less than 4 words or greater than 20 words.

Tokenization

In this step the sentences are broken down into groups of words each of length 1 to 4 called ngrams. For example, the 4-grams for the sentence “the rain in Spain falls mainly on the plain”,“economic news has little effect on financial markets” would be,

##  [1] "the rain in Spain"           "rain in Spain falls"        
##  [3] "in Spain falls mainly"       "Spain falls mainly on"      
##  [5] "falls mainly on the"         "mainly on the plain"        
##  [7] "economic news has little"    "news has little effect"     
##  [9] "has little effect on"        "little effect on financial" 
## [11] "effect on financial markets"

It is important to note that the ngrams are formed only within the boundary of the sentence (i.e.,) ngrams between sentences such as “on the plain economic”, “the plain economic news”, etc are not formed. The NGramTokenizer from RWeka package takes care of this by default. The frequencies are also recorded. This will help us find the probabilities of occurrence for each of the ngrams.

Total n-gram generated: The frequencies of the n-gram terms are very sparsely distributed, approximate 90% of terms are very rarely used, only appears couple times, they are of no use for training the word predicting model and can be ignored for quick predictions. Appendix 2 shows the plot of the Top 20 ngrams from the combined corpus. Appendix 3 shows the plot of ngram frequencies and is evident that the ngrams are sparse.

Word Prediction Algorithm

There are various techniques. The most common is the Simple Good Turing. So given any phrase or sentence, only the last few words are considered to form ngrams - 1,2,3. First the 3-gram is searched in the 4-gram table. If the input phrase is not in 4-gram table, the 3-gram table is considered. If there are matches, the trigrams with the highest probability are considered for the prediction. The end words that complete the selected trigrams are the new predicted words. But the limitation is that the probabilities are heavily dependent on the individual ngram sample size and not across different ngrams. One way to overcome this is to use the markov chain probability property P(A,B) = P(B|A) * P(A).

For example, P(I do not know) = P(know|I do not) * P(not|I do) * P(do|I) * P(I). From the below consolidated probability table (top 2 rows): P(I do not know) = 1.492427e-04 * 0.0006115575 * 0.0007181714 * 0.01584086 = 1.038334e-12

##      Gram3 Gram2 Gram1  Word Freq          Gram4         P1           P2
## 1 i do not  i do     i  know  584  i do not know 0.01584086 0.0007181714
## 2 i do not  i do     i think  368 i do not think 0.01584086 0.0007181714
##             P3           P4            P
## 1 0.0006115575 1.492427e-04 1.038334e-12
## 2 0.0006115575 9.404333e-05 6.542928e-13
